      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA process meets Gradation 1 requirement for MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 is a commercially licensed solver with ISO 9001-certified QA procedures. Version control logs and release notes confirm the solver build used for this study. No contraindications to software integrity have been reported in the solver's published errata for the turbulence and scalar transport modules employed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented benchmark test suite results for relevant physics (incompressible rotating flow, scalar transport) confirm solver correctness at Gradation 1.",
      "rationale": "The solver vendor's verification test suite covers rotating-frame incompressible flow and passive scalar transport. Published benchmark comparisons show agreement with analytical solutions. No failure modes have been observed in the relevant solver modules across prior studies using this solver version for blood pump applications."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) less than 5% for hemolysis index QoI across three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was performed using coarse (4.2M cells), medium (11.8M cells), and fine (28.6M cells) meshes. Richardson extrapolation yields GCI values of 3.1% and 1.8% for the coarse-to-medium and medium-to-fine transitions respectively for the normalised hemolysis index. The medium mesh is selected for production runs. Discretization error is bounded within the 5% acceptance threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) are documented and match simulated boundary conditions within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "Bench test conditions are documented in the experimental protocol: flow rates 2–6 L/min in 1 L/min increments, rotational speed 2400–3200 RPM, bovine blood at 37°C with haematocrit 35±2%. Boundary conditions in the CFD model are set to match measured values. Fluid property deviations between simulation and experiment are within 2% for viscosity and density."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted relative hemolysis index RH agrees with experimental measurements within 15% across all 5 operating points; pressure head within 5%.",
      "rationale": "Predicted RH values at all five operating points fall within 11% of bench measurements. Maximum deviation is 10.8% at the 6 L/min, 2400 RPM condition. Pressure-head predictions agree within 4.2% across the full operating envelope. Output comparison meets the stated acceptance criteria."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (RH index, pressure head, wall shear stress) are directly linked to the clinical decision criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate).",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI, the normalised hemolysis index RH, is the same metric used in the regulatory acceptance criterion. Secondary QoIs (pressure head, wall shear stress distribution) are mechanistically linked to erythrocyte damage mechanisms captured by the power-law hemolysis model. QoI relevance to the COU is confirmed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on the same FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at overlapping operating conditions with CPB clinical range.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, which is the subject of the COU. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB range (2–6 L/min, 2400–3200 RPM). Fluid analogue properties are within acceptable bounds for bovine blood as a surrogate. Validation activities are considered sufficiently relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Residual convergence to at least 1e-5 for all transport equations; mass imbalance below 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations were run to convergence with scaled residuals below 1e-6 for continuity, momentum, and scalar transport equations. Global mass imbalance is less than 0.005% in all cases. Iterative solver error is negligible relative to discretization error. No issues have been encountered with solver divergence or oscillatory non-convergence across any of the 25 simulation cases executed for this study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by a second analyst; boundary condition inputs verified against experimental protocol documentation.",
      "rationale": "An independent reviewer confirmed boundary condition assignments, material property inputs, and post-processing scripts against the documented experimental protocol. Discrepancies identified during review were resolved prior to production runs. No use errors have been observed following the independent review process."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model selection and hemolysis power-law model are justified by literature precedent for rotating blood pump applications at the Reynolds numbers of interest.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model is selected based on established precedent for confined rotating flow in blood pumps (Hariharan et al., 2011; Stewart et al., 2012). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model is the standard formulation for RH index prediction in regulatory submissions. Model form uncertainty is acknowledged but considered acceptable at MRL 2 given the comparative (relative) nature of the acceptance criterion. No failure modes related to turbulence model selection have been observed in the validation comparisons performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sensitivity of RH prediction to key input parameters (haematocrit, fluid viscosity, power-law exponents) quantified; variation within clinical range does not alter rank-ordering of operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis was performed for haematocrit (30–40%), dynamic viscosity (±5%), and power-law model coefficients (±10% per published uncertainty ranges). RH values shift by up to 8% across the sensitivity range, but the rank-ordering of worst-case operating conditions is preserved in all cases. Model inputs are assessed as adequate for the intended comparative use."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; experimental sample characterisation beyond basic fluid property documentation is not required.",
      "rationale": "This factor is not assessed at Model Risk Level 2 for a comparative hemolysis study. Basic fluid property documentation is provided under Test Conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
